list of more than one name then the names are separated\n   151\t     * by a comma character. Each provider class is a {@code public} class with a\n   152\t     * {@code public} constructor that has one formal parameter of type {@code\n   153\t     * FileSystemProvider}. If the provider class is in a named module then the module\n   154\t     * exports the package containing the provider class to at least {@code java.base}.\n   155\t     * Each provider class is loaded, using the\n   156\t     * {@linkplain ClassLoader#getSystemClassLoader() default system class loader},\n   157\t     * and instantiated by invoking the constructor. The providers are loaded and\n   158\t     * instantiated in the order they are listed in the property.\n   159\t     * If this process fails or a provider's scheme is not equal to {@code \"file\"}\n   160\t     * then an unspecified error is thrown. URI schemes are normally compared\n   161\t     * without regard to case but for the default provider, the scheme is\n   162\t     * required to be {@code \"file\"}. The first provider class is instantiated\n   163\t     * by invoking it with a reference to the system-default provider.\n   164\t     * The second provider class is instantiated by invoking it with a reference\n   165\t     * to the first provider instance. The third provider class is instantiated\n   166\t     * by invoking it with a reference to the second instance, and so on. The\n   167\t     * last provider to be instantiated becomes the default provider; its {@code\n   168\t     * getFileSystem} method is invoked with the URI {@code \"file:///\"} to\n   169\t     * get a reference to the default file system.\n   170\t     *\n   171\t     * <p> Subsequent invocations of this method return the file system that was\n   172\t     * returned by the first invocation.\n   173\t     *\n   174\t     * @return  the default file system\n   175\t     */\n   176\t    public static FileSystem getDefault() {\n   177\t        if (VM.isMod